   "common": [
      {
         "text": "### Introduction\n\nThousands of years ago, Socrates concluded something that is cited in different texts from *History Tracers* (<htcite0>; <htcite1>):",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 0,
               "uuid": "3b95809f-e017-4f2c-9c30-bc3db69ce7c5",
               "text": "Plato",
               "page": "pp. 15",
               "date_time": {
                  "type": "gregory",
                  "year": "1899",
                  "month": "-1",
                  "day": "-1"
               }
            },
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "ae49cb80-7652-4fe9-b18a-0de1c4c8321a",
               "text": "Luiz Felipe Pondé",
               "page": "",
               "date_time": {
                  "type": "gregory",
                  "year": "2024",
                  "month": "9",
                  "day": "10"
               }
            }
         ],
         "date_time": null,
         "isTable": false,
         "imgdesc": "",
         "format": "markdown",
         "PostMention": ""
      },
      {
         "text": "<ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"I neither know, nor think I know\"</i></li> </ul>",
         "source": null,
         "date_time": null,
         "isTable": false,
         "imgdesc": "",
         "format": "html",
         "PostMention": ""
      },
      {
         "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: This is very profound, except...</b><br /><br />The recognition that knowledge is gigantic and that we know little, expressed by Socrates' phrase, is very beautiful. This is not the only way it presents itself to the population; it is also mentioned more directly: “I only know that I know nothing.”<br /><br />Suppose there is something you have believed for many years, even though not a single piece of evidence has ever emerged to support it. If a new discovery could show that your conclusion is inaccurate and that there is something beyond it, how would you behave?</div></div></center></p>",
         "source": null,
         "date_time": null,
         "isTable": false,
         "imgdesc": "",
         "format": "html",
         "PostMention": ""
      },
      {
         "text": "#### The origin\n\nThe origin of the peoples of *Abya Yala* (America) has already been studied in History Tracers through a proposal by José de Acosta who, as early as <htdate0>, suggested that the arrival of indigenous peoples would have occurred via Asia (**Figure 4**) (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nCenturies after the initial proposal, we can confirm José de Acosta's conclusion not only by the appearance of indigenous peoples from north to south of the continent, but also thanks to the collection of genetic data in Asia and in Abya Yala, which confirmed these connections (<htcite2>; <htcite3>; <htcie4>; <htcite5>).",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "c2f6de96-6589-4f66-858e-259bf3f3046a",
               "text": "Acosta, José",
               "page": "pp. 240",
               "date_time": {
                  "type": "gregory",
                  "year": "1590",
                  "month": "-1",
                  "day": "-1"
               }
            },
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "1070f062-f6c1-4cc5-8732-83b31c8e5137",
               "text": "History Tracers Team",
               "page": "Indigenous of <i>Abya Yala</i> (América)",
               "date_time": {
                  "type": "gregory",
                  "year": "2025",
                  "month": "",
                  "day": ""
               }
            },
            {
