         "id": "6c46b554-acc0-4730-a6a8-504893a07c7c",
         "name": "The Clovis Hypothesis",
         "history": [
            {
               "text": "#### The initial understanding\n\nOur initial understanding of the arrival of the first populations in *Abya Yala* (America) is directly linked to the extinction of a megafauna that lived on the continent and which, among other animals, included the presence of mammoths (**Figure 5**). However, the period of human arrival is not a unanimous conclusion.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"mamut\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('mamut', '0%')\" /><b>Figure 5</b>: Mammoth fossil exhibited in Mexico. Photograph taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the National Museum of Anthropology in Mexico (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0be2ea18-ab78-4cb1-b3be-1ff0ba4ade95",
                     "text": "Museo Nacional de Antropologia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "Nesta imagem vemos a parte debaixo do maxiliar de um mamute extindo a milhares de anos.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The “Clovis first” proposal\n\nThe settlement proposal called “Clovis first” tells us that people living in the Clovis region built tools from bones, stones, and points, like the one shown in **Figure 6** exhibited at the British Museum, spreading first through the current territory of the United States and then southward into the continent (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nEvidence supporting this movement includes artifacts found from Mexico to Venezuela (<htcite2>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "880dfb74-605b-483c-9c9e-fee8518acc73",
                     "text": "Waters, M. R., & Stafford, T. W., Jr.",
                     "page": "pp. 1122 - 1123",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2007",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "8e3c4eca-abc0-4178-b097-ea1740b73d2d",
                     "text": "The British Museum",
                     "page": "Clovis Point",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "880dfb74-605b-483c-9c9e-fee8518acc73",
                     "text": "Waters, M. R., & Stafford, T. W., Jr.",
                     "page": "pp. 1123",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2007",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgPoint\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPoint', '0%')\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 6</b>: Clovis point projectile exhibited at the British Museum. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite0> ).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "8e3c4eca-abc0-4178-b097-ea1740b73d2d",
                     "text": "The British Museum",
                     "page": "Clovis Point",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "In addition to the material evidence, genetic expansion models show that a single migratory population could have occurred and expanded across the continent (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "94372b4a-825c-4b76-a252-625274cb17b4",
                     "text": "Fagundes, N. J. R. et al.",
                     "page": "pp. 587 - 589",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2008",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Everything solved?</b><br /><br />We have an archaeological model that possesses data collected from different parts of the continent.<br /><br />We have a genetic model that shows that just one migration across the entire continent is possible.<br /><br />Therefore, we conclude that if we put the two together, we will solve all the questions about the arrival of humans in the Americas <i>Abya Yala</i> (America).<br /><br />Can you imagine scenarios that could invalidate the previous conclusion?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            }
         ],
